  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">The Passphrase Alternative</h2>
  <p>If you need a password you can actually type from memory, consider using a passphrase: a string of four to six random, unrelated words. For example, "correct-horse-battery-staple" is both strong and memorable. A passphrase with four random words from a dictionary of 7,776 words provides roughly 50 bits of entropy, which is quite strong for most use cases.</p>
  <p class="mt-3">The key is that the words must be truly random, not a phrase that makes sense. "I-love-my-dog" is not a good passphrase because it is predictable. Use a generator or roll dice with a word list like EFF's diceware list for true randomness.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Password Manager Tips</h2>
  <p>With unique passwords for every account, you cannot realistically remember them all. A password manager solves this problem by securely storing all your passwords behind one master password. Here are some tips:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mt-4">
    <li><strong>Choose a reputable manager</strong> &mdash; Options like Bitwarden (free and open source), 1Password, or KeePass are well-regarded and regularly audited.</li>
    <li><strong>Create a strong master password</strong> &mdash; This is the one password you do need to remember. Use a long passphrase (five or more random words) that you can commit to memory.</li>
    <li><strong>Enable two-factor authentication</strong> &mdash; Protect your password manager with 2FA. This ensures that even if someone learns your master password, they still cannot access your vault.</li>
    <li><strong>Use the built-in generator</strong> &mdash; Most password managers include a password generator. Use it to create unique passwords for new accounts directly.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit regularly</strong> &mdash; Periodically review your stored passwords. Check for reused or weak passwords and update them.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Enable Two-Factor Authentication</h2>
  <p>A strong password is your first line of defense, but two-factor authentication (2FA) adds a critical second layer. With 2FA enabled, an attacker who obtains your password still cannot log in without the second factor, typically a code from an authenticator app or a physical security key. Enable 2FA on every account that supports it, especially email, banking, and social media.</p>

